 I would say this, to get a TT job in the humanities, you will need to enter the PhD with a fierce motivation to give it your all.

- /u/Adarga

You will also a detailed plan for how you can become a competitive candidate when you finish and enter the job market. Luck is often a factor in the hiring process: scholar X likes your work and decides to fight for you to be on the shortlist, scholar Y received some unrelated good news before reviewing your application, etc. But aside from luck, my experience has been that most successful early-career candidates just know how to play the game. 

They follow the same basic formula: 

- Finish your studies in 4-6 years;
- Publish a couple articles in top-tier journals;
- Write your diss in a way that you can transform it into a book;
- Teach a couple courses on your own and avoid the adjunct trap;
- Understand the trends in your field/sub-fields and play to them;
- Learn how to speak confidently and concisely about your work;
- Do not waste time on projects that have little value to hiring committees (e. g. organizing conferences in your department, attending so-called 'grad' conferences or submitting to 'grad' publications, writing blog posts instead of publishing in peer-reviewed journals, etc.).

Some people will say that they did not follow this formula and still managed to find a TT position; they are clearly in the minority here. Most of your colleagues in your PhD program won't have a plan and may not even really understand what is required to succeed. Make damned sure you are not one of them.

I followed this formula and got the dream job in my first year on the market. Yes I was lucky. Yes my comment is evidence of survivorship bias. But I also just finished serving on a hiring committee and looking through applications from early- and mid-career scholars and I'm more certain than ever that there[.] value in this formula.
